<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06285033 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06285033 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; Photo: (Tony LaRussa Baseball, computer game)  </CAPTION><LEADPARA>  Computer owners who'd like to be in command in the dugout themselves have theopportunity to play manager with two new games endorsed by men who have beenWorld Series winners.;   &quot;Tony LaRussa Baseball,&quot; pictured (StrategicSimulations Inc., $49.95 for both IBM and Commodore 64 computers), featuresplayers with special streak and clutch performances ratings, digitalizedvoices, a full-season play mode, and a detailed ball park that accounts forwind and turf conditions. The IBM version requires a EGA or VGA/MCGA monitor,hard drive, and a 3 1/2 inch double density or 5 1/4 inch high-density diskdrive.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Living  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FIELDING A DREAM OF TEAMS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  What's Hot!  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;Earl Weaver Baseball II&quot; (Electronic Arts, $49.95 for IBM/Tandy) includesanimated full-screen batters, a new statistics system that allows owners tokeep the game more current and a variety of camera angles of on-field action.EGA, VGA/MCGA or Tandy graphics are required. (A version for the Sega Genesisvideo game system will be released early next year.);   Both are available atlocal computer software stores or by calling (800) 245-4525.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  -- Steve Marinucci  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911011  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  October  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  182  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, October 11, 199100285033,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>